nary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  French: habitational name from any of the places so called, for example in Normandy, named from a religious dedication to a (male) St. Clair.","2  North American variant spelling of   St  .   Claire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Claire","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."]}]},{"name":"Hilary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Hillary   and  compare  Ellery  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hillary","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Ciaran.","English (of Norman origin):","from the Middle English and Old French male or female personal name <i>Hilari(e)</i>, <i>Ilari(e)</i>, and <i>Elari(e)</i>, from Latin <i>Hilarius</i> and <i>Hilaria</i> ‘joyful’ (from Greek <i>hilaros</i>). The Latin name was chosen by many early Christians to express their joy and hope of salvation, and was borne by several saints, including a 4th-century bishop of Poitiers (died 368) noted for his vigorous resistance to the Arian heresy, and a 5th-century bishop of Arles. Largely due to veneration of Saint Hilarius of Poitiers, the name became popular in France in the forms <i>Hilari</i> and <i>Hilaire</i>, and was brought to England by the Norman conquerors. Although quite popular in France, it was only occasionally used in England, where it was confused with the name in 2 below."]},{"name":"Ellery","meanings":["variant of   Hillary  .","habitational name from Elleray in Windermere (Westmorland), probably from Old Norse <i>elri</i> ‘alder’ + <i>vrá</i> ‘nook’.","English:"]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma St Hilary was born in 1120, in Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland. She married William De Vieuxpont I. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1120–Deceased":"1120–Surnud","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1130–1203":"1130–1203","1134–Male":"1134–Surnud","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1203":"1203","1134":"1134","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1120–Deceased":"1120–Kuollut","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1130–1203":"1130–1203","1134–Male":"1134–Kuollut","1120–Female":"1120–Kuollut","1203":"1203","1134":"1134","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1120–Deceased":"1120–Décédée","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1130–1203":"1130–1203","1134–Male":"1134–Décédé","1120–Female":"1120–Décédée","1203":"1203","1134":"1134","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Emma St Hilary est née en 1120, à Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Écosse. Elle a épousé William De Vieuxpont I. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils."},"de":{"1120–Deceased":"1120–Verstorben","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1130–1203":"1130–1203","1134–Male":"1134–Verstorben","1120–Female":"1120–Verstorben","1203":"1203","1134":"1134","1110":"1110","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1174":"1174","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshir